SSH Access control and Session Termination

What I did:
Connected to Ubuntu from Kali via SSH after multiple attempts
Observed both failed and successful login attempts in /var/log/auth.log
Attempted to block access by:
Denying port 22 in ufw
Stopping the ssh service
Noticed that the active ssh session remained connected
Identified the active ssh session:
ps aux | grep sshd
Terminated the session by killing the process:
kill (PID)
Blocked new ssh connections using ufw

What I learned:
Existing ssh sessions remain active even if ssh service is stopped or port is blocked
Firewall rules affect new connections, not already established ones
Each ssh session runs as its own process, which can be indentified and terminated using its PID
Killing the ssh session process is required to immediately disconnect an active user
There's a difference between service control (systemctl), network control (ufw), and process control (pid/kill)

This simulates a basic incident response scenario where an active unauthorized session must be identified and terminated
